Based on my search, here's what I found about programmatically adding clips to a timeline and manipulating sequences in Premiere Pro CEP panels:

## Adding Clips to Timeline Programmatically

The code for bringing clips into a sequence can be found in the sample panel JSX under the insert or append and overwrite functions. To insert a clip in a sequence, you get the clip from the Project panel, access the active sequence, and use `insertClip()`:

```javascript
// insert clip in sequence
var first = app.project.rootItem.children[0];
var seq = app.project.activeSequence;
var vTrack1 = seq.videoTracks[0];
vTrack1.insertClip(first, '00;00;00;00');
```

To append to the last element in a sequence:
```javascript
if (vTrack1.clips.numItems > 0){
    var lastClip = vTrack1.clips[(vTrack1.clips.numItems - 1)];
    if (lastClip){
        vTrack1.insertClip(first, lastClip.end.seconds);
    }
}
```

## Manipulating Clip Timing in Sequence

You can trim clips in a sequence by adjusting their start and end times:

```javascript
var clip1 = app.project.activeSequence.videoTracks[0].clips[0];
var endTime = clip1.end;
endTime.seconds = 50;
var startTime = clip1.start;
startTime.seconds = 10;
clip1.start = startTime;
clip1.end = endTime;
```

## Setting In/Out Points

You'll need the in/out points set for the master clip first before inserting into a sequence.(no content)You can set in points on a particular project item that is only in the project panel, not in the source monitor. The workflow involves opening a file in the source monitor, finding the clip with the same path in the project panel, setting in and out points, and then bringing it into the sequence.

## Important Limitations

There is no current API method (DOM, QE, CEP, or UXP) that can move an existing clip vertically between tracks. Premiere Pro no longer includes a keyboard mappable command like Move Clip Up/Down Between Tracks, meaning even UI automation cannot rely on a universal shortcut.(no content)Mimicking in-timeline editing is not possible through ExtendScript as of today, but you can try to mimic classical 3-point editing through a script if your marker information is of such quality that you can calculate the time values for the source clips.

## CEP vs UXP

UXP in Premiere Pro is in beta and very new, so lots of APIs haven't been built yet. If you need a production panel today or in the near future, you're going to need to build it in CEP.

## Reference Code

The official Adobe CEP sample panel is the best reference for this functionality: [Adobe-CEP/Samples - Premiere.jsx](https://github.com/Adobe-CEP/Samples/blob/master/PProPanel/jsx/PPRO/Premiere.jsx)


